body.text:
I was taking the college entrance exams twice. 
The first time, I got accepted to Harvard University. 
The second time, I got accepted to Stanford College.
But both schools took one look at my name and refused to admit me.
I thought maybe it was because I failed some kind of background check. 
But my parents are just humble farmers. 
Forget criminal records—they wouldn't even hurt a fly. 
Then came my third attempt at the entrance exams. 
Once again, I scored in the top percentile. 
This time, I applied to Columbia University, thinking I was finally in the clear. 
But the initially enthusiastic admissions officer took one look at my name and froze. 
Right then and there, he declared with absolute certainty that Columbia couldn't accept me. 
For the life of me, I couldn't figure out what was wrong with my name. 
Why would every university turn me away the moment they saw it, despite my outstanding test scores?

"You must be this year's top-scoring student, Scarlett Winters."
"Columbia University will not be admitting you. We simply cannot accept a student like you!"
The Columbia admissions officer verified my personal information right in front of me, then firmly shook his head.
My heart sank as all my hopes evaporated, leaving me feeling utterly helpless.
Desperate to understand why, I couldn't stop myself from asking.
"Why can't you admit me when I literally have the highest score in the state?"
"At least tell me the truth so I can understand what's happening!"
Facing my questions, the admissions officer merely gave me a dismissive glance.
He said, "No school would ever accept a student like you!"
I struggled to make sense of his words, but no matter how hard I racked my brain, I couldn't figure out what he meant.
Completely devastated, I collapsed to the floor, my body trembling as I broke down sobbing.
My mind was swimming with questions.
Why, after scoring at the top of the state three times in a row, was no university willing to accept me?
The first time I took the entrance exams, I scored 98% and got into Harvard University.
Just when I was excitedly waiting for my acceptance letter, I received news that my application had been withdrawn.
I couldn't believe it, so I called the admissions office.
But as soon as the administrator heard my name was Scarlett Winters, they didn't investigate further and simply said, "We will not be admitting you."
After a year of additional study, I took the exams a second time, scoring 99% and getting into Stanford College.
I thought, surely Stanford would accept me.
But the result was exactly the same—my application was rejected again.
When I called to investigate again, the Stanford admissions director, just like the one at Harvard, refused to admit me as soon as they heard my name.
I just couldn't understand it. My scores kept improving, yet why Harvard and Stanford wouldn't dare accept me?!

At first, I thought there might be an issue with my background check, so I specifically looked into whether my parents had any criminal history.
But the results showed that my family had been completely law-abiding for three generations.
Besides, my parents were humble farmers who, as I said, wouldn't even hurt a fly.
Unable to find the truth but refusing to give up, I determinedly took the entrance exams for a third time.
This time I scored 99.5%, once again at the top of my class.
Considering my previous experiences, I didn't apply to Harvard or Stanford, but instead put Columbia University as my first choice.
With my score, I should have easily gotten into Columbia.
Unfortunately, the admissions officer hit me with devastating news.
Upon seeing my name, he immediately declared that Columbia wouldn't accept me.
Once again, I wasn't admitted.
After experiencing rejection three times, I was utterly desperate.
My parents, watching me sob uncontrollably, also broke into tears.
"How could this happen?"
"My daughter has the highest score in the state—how could she not be admitted?"
The elderly couple couldn't believe the outcome either.
We drove to Columbia College and happened to meet the admissions officer who was about to leave right at the gate.
Without hesitation, My mom, eyes bloodshot with grief, fell to her knees with a thud right in the middle of the office.
She pleaded desperately, "Please, I'm begging you, let my daughter attend college. Whatever it costs, we'll find a way to pay it!"
The admissions officer remained unmoved.
My mom, beyond reasoning now, bowed her head to the ground.
She scraped her forehead against the tile until it bled, reaching out to clutch the officer's pant leg.
Through her tears and runny nose, her voice broke as she said, "Sir, my child needs an education! Her father and I have worked the land our whole lives. Our greatest wish is to give our daughter a chance for a better life than ours, so she doesn't have to endure the hardships we did. I'm begging you, please help us!"
My dad also dropped to his knees beside her.
"Sir, I may not be educated, but I know my daughter is the top student. She absolutely needs to go to college!"
"Without a college education, her future will be ruined. I'm begging you to help us!"
Watching my parents, who had never bowed their heads to anyone before, now humbling themselves and begging on my behalf, I felt waves of pain washing over my heart.
Though we were farmers, my parents had never been this humiliated, no matter how hard they worked or how much they suffered.
But it was all in vain.
The admissions officer wasn't moved in the slightest. He repeated the same response: "Please don't do this. We simply cannot accept Scarlett Winters!"
My dad, thinking he hadn't shown enough sincerity, pulled his sleeve over his hand and started polishing the officer's shoes.
He begged while polishing, even knocking his forehead to the ground again.
Despite all this, the admissions officer wouldn't budge: "These dramatics won't work. No matter what, we cannot accept a student like Scarlett Winters."
The admissions officer was absolutely resolute. No matter how much my parents pleaded, he refused to engage with us any further.
After the meeting, Columbia officially rejected my application. I, the person at the center of all this, was completely baffled.
I tried to find the reason within myself.
What did he mean by "a student like you"?
What terrible mistake had I committed?

In my memory, I couldn't find even the tiniest blemish.
Since childhood, I'd been an exemplary student with perfect grades and behavior—the kind other parents held up as a role model for their kids.
Seeing my distress, my parents gathered around to comfort me.
Dad stroked my hair.
"Scarlett, it's okay. If this university doesn't want you, we'll try others. There are so many colleges in the country—surely one will accept you!"
Mom wiped my tears and agreed.
"My Scarlett is the top student in the state. There's definitely a college for you. No matter what, Dad and Mom will fight for you!"
My parents' hair had grayed considerably after my three failed college attempts.
After my first rejection, they willingly spent money to enroll me in prep classes.
They assured me not to worry, that Dad would always have my back.
After the second rejection, they hired expensive tutors for me.
They worked multiple jobs, finding every possible way to earn money to support me.
My parents had always given to me unconditionally.
The reason my entrance exam scores improved each time was because of their sacrifices.
But our family's third chance had ended in failure again.
At that moment, I felt like I had failed my parents terribly.
Looking at their aged faces and rough hands, I choked back tears as I apologized:
"Dad, Mom, I'm so sorry. It's all my fault. I've disappointed you again!"
"I'm just a burden. I've only dragged you down!"
Of course, my parents didn't blame me. They just told me not to think such thoughts.
That night, I tossed and turned in bed, trying to make sense of everything.
Columbia had rejected my application, so I could only hope that my second-choice school would accept me.
During my first two attempts, I'd been so confident about Harvard and Stanford that I hadn't listed any other schools, resulting in both institutions rejecting me.
This time, I'd been more cautious.
Although my scores would have easily secured me a spot at Columbia, I had also applied to regular state universities.
I'd even gone so far as to apply to community colleges with the lowest admission standards, fearing rejection from the state schools.
I thought, if the prestigious universities wouldn't take me, perhaps a regular state school would—after all, I was still the top-scoring student in the state.
Sure enough, hope finally arrived.
When the regular state university released its acceptance list, my name was on it.
As the school heard that a top-scoring student with a 99.5% had applied to their institution, they arrived at our house the very next day with a delegation, complete with fanfare to welcome me.
Seeing the crowd at our door, my parents and I finally had smiles on our faces.
The university administrators rushed forward to greet my parents.
"Our university is incredibly honored to receive the attention of the state's top student!"
"You've raised an exceptional child. I assure you, at our school, your daughter will be treated like a national treasure."
Hearing these words, my parents' eyes gleamed with joy.
Mom squeezed my hand, happily saying that my suffering had finally paid off.
Dad stood up straighter, his pride evident.
The atmosphere was warm and celebratory.
The administrator quickly presented the acceptance letter they had prepared in advance. With a beaming smile, he opened it.
"Scarlett Winters, after careful review, we are pleased to inform you that you have been accepted to..."
Just as the administrator was enthusiastically reading the contents, he suddenly stopped.
His eyes fixed on the acceptance letter, he froze completely.
Two minutes later, he looked up at me and asked, "Scarlett Winters? Are you certain that's your name?"
Seeing the administrator's expression, my heart sank with a sense of foreboding.
Before I could answer, my parents responded for me.
"Yes, sir, what's the matter?"
Upon hearing their confirmation, the administrator staggered backward.
He waved for the celebratory fanfare to stop, and the scene immediately fell silent.
Seeing this, my parents grew anxious.
They turned to look at me, but my eyes were locked on the administrator's lips as he prepared to speak.
His voice was cold: "I'm sorry, but our university cannot accept you. I will report this to the admissions office and withdraw your acceptance."
